text:
Hopefully someone passes on the info to Gawr Gura that Youtube's video compression has been known to cause problems with viewers watching videos of dark spaces.

 "Youtube's version of the video" is basically over enhancing the darkness of the streamer's video; so even when you enhance the brightness, the "Youtube video" is still auto-enhancing the image. 

This means the video can be overly-bright for the person playing/recording/streaming the game while all the viewers see is an image with excessive darkness.

The excessive darkness causes the viewers to lose track of basic shapes & objects in scenes where the regular viewer should be able to see the general outline of objects. Sometimes streamers enhance the gamma too much and the result doesn't fix the problem it just means viewers see "grey blobs" instead of "black blobs". 

It's a compression issue from my understanding and IDK how some people get around it but Gawr should at least be informed she might need to change something about her upload settings to alleviate the "too dark to see at max brightness" problem

text:
Theta is easily the weakest and least scary place in the game for me, the proxy enemies are insanely easy and pose almost no threat, and the lab section was all brightly lit corridors and rooms

the start of the game when you first wake up in PATHOS-II, Omicron, and the start bit of Tau with Yoshida as an enemy were probably the game's strongest areas that best used the tone to make you feel unsettled and scared
author: @assistantmagus5213

text:
¬†@assistantmagus5213¬† I still stand by Theta being downright horrifying. Akers and the Proxies relying on sound is freaky and the fact that Akers can instantly spawn nearby if you run and just randomly as you explore in the lab areas is freaky enough. I always find something disturbing about blind enemies that rely on sound.

Tau wasn't that scary tbh. Jin Yoshida doesn't really chase if you look at him. He just stops. You can treat him like a weeping angel/scp-173 and easily get past the rather short area then he just never returns ever. Kinda wish he was more of a threat in Tau.

Omicron was underwhelming as well. Just 2 incredibly short encounters with the robot girl that doesn't do anything unless you somehow don't pay attention to the obvious clues that she's disturbed by sound.

Oddly enough, I found the underwater ship with the Fleshers (creatures you aren't supposed to look at) to be the most terrifying area in the entire game aside from Theta. I spent so long hiding too scared to advance and I took every possible wrong way before I took the correct way meanwhile every YouTuber/streamer I've watched afterwards has somehow magoo'd their way through the whole thing rather flawlessly and quickly.
